    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac, Af). Small stands occur in the Santa Cruz Mountains (Sikes et al. 2021) and as far north as Contra Costa Co. on steep slopes, usually adjacent to stands of the <i>Artemisia californica</i> alliance. Stands are predicted to occur elsewhere on steep coastal slopes.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Af). Stands occur at Pinnacles National Monument on steep slopes with a variety of herbs (Kittel et al. 2012), and stands are predicted elsewhere.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ao). Stands occur on slopes within the Camanche Terraces.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Al). Stands of <i>Diplacus aurantiacus</i> occur on steep slopes and ridgetops in Southern Marin County (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fc-d). Stands from Tulare to Kern Cos. occupy steep, rocky, north-facing slopes and road cuts.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-c, Be-j). Stands occur in the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler- Wolf and Evens 2006), coastal San Diego Co., and in the northern Channel Islands. On Santa Cruz Island (as D. flemingii), stands associate with <i>Artemisia californica, Hazardia squarrosa, Isocoma menziesii, Quercus pacifica, Quercus agrifolia,</i> and <i>Pinus muricata</i> alliances. Stands dominated by <i>Diplacus puniceus</i> occur on Santa Catalina Island (Dixon et al. 2019).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Diplacus aurantiacus </i>is planted along highway corridors, and it is widely used in habitat restoration. Summer water extends the plant’s flowering and leaf production period, but watered plants are more susceptible to air pollution because they uptake sodium oxide (Montalvo and McMillan 2002a). </div>
</div>

    

    

